Safer Food for Boston

Project Summary

Hello and welcome to the main page for my capstone project. This project is to predict restaurant health violations in the city of Boston using machine learning. The aim is to provide governmental inspectors with more tools and resources to predict when a restaurant will be in violation. They could then inspect a specific restaurant ahead of schedule, compared to their regular annual inspection. This could lead to violations being caught earlier with a resulting reduction in food borne illness in the general population.

This approach has been performed before by the city of Chicago, by Open Data Nation for Montgomery County, Maryland, and for pro-bono work for Open Data Nation concerning Washington, D.C.. This work is additional pro-bono work, in support of Open Data Nation's FIVAR model. More data collection, cleaning, analysis, and modeling is still in progress and is to be reported in the future. Please scroll through the website (watch out for the heatmaps with the mouse scroll wheel!), and if you have any comments or questions, please contact me.

Restaurants That Passed Inspection in 2015

This is a heatmap of the Boston restaurants that passed inspection in 2015. This has not been normalized for population density or for density of restaurants in a given area. There is significant overlap between this figure and the figure below, which shows Boston restaurants that failed inspection in 2015. This is consistent with the exploratory analysis which showed that ~50% of Boston restaurants passed inspection, while ~50% of Boston restaurants failed inspection. More work needs to be performed to further separate and analyze the data.

Restaurants That Failed Inspection in 2015

Exploratory Analysis

Some of the initial analysis involved visualizing the inspection data with histograms. Both the counts of the violation per zipcode and violations per category are shown below in their respective graphs. The results are not normalized for population density or for density of restaurants in a given area. Both graphs show that there are outliers for specific geographic regions, or violation categories, respectively.

Website Updates

This website is in progress. Other work including additional wrangling and data analysis is still being performed, while machine learning (clustering and classification) has been performed, but not posted yet to the website. Stay tuned for future updates!

Jonathan Boyle 2016
